==Broadcasting standards==
Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept 1080p signals in native resolution format, which means there are a true 1920 pixels in width and 1080 pixels in height, and the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution. The  logo program, by , requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning .
For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second is currently being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition.  has been endorsing 1080p50 as a  production format because it improves resolution and requires no , allows broadcasting of standard 1080i25 and 720p50 signal alongside 1080p50 even in the current infrastructure and is compatible with  distribution formats.
1080p50/p60 production format requires a whole new range of studio equipment including cameras, storage and editing systems, and contribution links (such as  and ) as it has doubled the data rate of current 50 or 60 fields interlaced 1920x1080 from 1.485&nbsp;Gbit/s to nominally 3&nbsp;Gbit/s using uncompressed RGB encoding. Most current revisions of ,  and EBU Tech 3299 require  color space and 4:2:2  for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08&nbsp;Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
Recent studies show that for digital broadcasts compressed with H.264/AVC, transmission bandwidth savings of  over fully progressive video are minimal even when using twice the frame rate; i.e., 1080p50 signal (50 progressive frames per second) actually produces the same bit rate as 1080i50 signal (25 interlaced frames or 50 sub-fields per second).
===ATSC===
In the United States, the original  for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as '''1080p24''', '''1080p25''' and '''1080p30''').
In July 2008, the ATSC standards were amended to include  compression and 1080p at 50, 59.94 and 60 frames per second ('''1080p50''' and '''1080p60'''). Such s require H.264/AVC '''', while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient  codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for .
